<section label="lhcc-eqns">
	<title> Homogeneous (LHCC) Equations </title>

	<introduction>
		<p>
			Before learning how to solve Linear Homogeneous Constant Coefficient (LHCC) differential equations, it's important to identify these equations and understand the nature of their structure. In this section, we‚Äôll define what it means for a differential equation to be homogeneous, review how constant coefficients affect the form of the equation, and formally define what qualifies as an LHCC equation.
		</p>
	</introduction>

	<paragraphs xml:id="homogeneous">
		<title> Homogeneous </title>

		<p>
			A linear differential equation is <term>homogeneous</term> if the right-hand side is zero‚Äîthat is, there is no forcing term. Otherwise, it is <term>nonhomogeneous</term>.
		</p>

		<p>
			For example, the following equations are homogeneous:
		</p>

		<me>
			x y'' - \cos x y' + 6y = 0, \qquad y''' + 2y'' = y'
		</me>

		<p>
			These are nonhomogeneous because of the (boxed) right-hand side:
		</p>

		<me>
			y'' + 4xy = \boxed{x}, \qquad y' + \boxed{e^x} = 0
		</me>

		<task label="chkpt-identifying-lhcc-1">
			<title> ‚ùìüëâ Identifying Homogeneous Equations </title>
			<statement>
				<p>
					Which of the following equations is homogeneous?
				</p>
			</statement>
			<choices randomize="yes">
				<choice correct="yes">
					<statement> <m>\ds\quad y'' + 4y' + 3y = 0 </m> </statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Correct! The right-hand side is zero, so the equation is homogeneous.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement> <m>\ds\quad y'' + 4y^2 = 0 </m> </statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. This equation looks homogeneous, but homogeneity only applies to linear equations.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement> <m>\ds\quad y'' + 4y' + 3y = 7 </m> </statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The equation has a non-zero constant term, making it non-homogeneous.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
				<choice>
					<statement> <m>\ds\quad y' + 2y = x^2 </m> </statement>
					<feedback>
						<p>
							Incorrect. The right-hand side has a non-zero function of <m>x</m>, so this is non-homogeneous.
						</p>
					</feedback>
				</choice>
			</choices>
		</task>
	</paragraphs>

	<paragraphs xml:id="definition-of-lhcc">
		<title> The LHCC Equation </title>

		<p>
		Putting it all together, we arrive at the definition of an LHCC equation.
		</p>

		<definition xml:id="def-lhcc-eqn">
			<statement>
				<p>
					A linear homogeneous differential equation with constant coefficients (LHCC) has the form:
				</p>
				<men xml:id="lhcc-equation">
					a_n\ y^{(n)} + \cdots + a_2\ y'' + a_1\ y' + a_0\ y = 0
				</men>
				<p>
					where all coefficients <m>a_n, \dots, a_0</m> are constants.
				</p>
			</statement>
		</definition>

		<p>
			The following equations are examples of LHCC equations:
		</p>

		<me>
			2y'' - 3y' + 5y = 0, \qquad \frac{d^2s}{dt^2} + \frac{ds}{dt} - 4s = 0 \qquad u'' = u
		</me>.
	</paragraphs>

	<objectives>
		<ul>
			<li> A differential equation is <term>homogeneous</term> if the right-hand side is zero‚Äîthere is no forcing function. </li>
			<li> An LHCC equation is a linear homogeneous differential equation whose coefficients are all constants. </li>
		</ul>
	</objectives>

	<task label="chkpt-identifying-lhcc-2">
		<title> ‚ùìüëâ Matching Equations with Properties </title>
		<statement>
			<p>
				Match each differential equation to its correct classification.
			</p>
		</statement>
		<feedback>
			<p>
				Good work! Recognizing equation types helps determine the best solution method.
			</p>
		</feedback>
		<cardsort>
			<match>
				<premise><m> y'' + 2y' + 3y = 0 </m></premise>
				<response>Linear, Homogeneous, Constant Coefficients</response>
			</match>
			<match>
				<premise><m> y'' = xy </m></premise>
				<response>Linear, Homogeneous, Nonconstant Coefficient</response>
			</match>
			<match>
				<premise><m> 3y'' + 2 = 0 </m></premise>
				<premise><m> y'' + 4y' + 3y = 7 </m></premise>
				<response>Linear, Nonhomogeneous, Constant Coefficient</response>
			</match>
			<match>
				<premise><m> 3y'' + y^2 = e^x </m></premise>
				<premise><m> yy' + y'' = 0 </m></premise>
				<response>Nonlinear</response>
			</match>
		</cardsort>
	</task>

	
